Why was it introduced?
----------------------
Before C++14, the compiler could not deduce a function's return type from its body.

C++11:

auto add(int a, int b) -> int
{
    return a + b;
}

C++14:

auto add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

--------------------------------------------------

How does the compiler deduce the return type?
---------------------------------------------
The compiler examines ALL return statements and deduces one common return type.

Example:

auto add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

Compiler deduces:

int add(int a, int b);

--------------------------------------------------

Important Rules
---------------

✔ Compiler checks ALL return statements.

✔ All return statements must deduce to the SAME type.

✔ If there is no return statement, the return type is deduced as `void`.

Example:

auto print()
{
    cout << "Hello";
}

// Equivalent to:
void print();

✔ Return type deduction happens at compile time.

✔ Recursive functions generally require an explicit return type.

--------------------------------------------------

Example: Valid
--------------

auto func(bool flag)
{
    if(flag)
        return 10;

    return 20;
}

Return type: int

--------------------------------------------------

Example: Invalid
----------------

auto func(bool flag)
{
    if(flag)
        return 10;

    return 3.14;
}

❌ Error:
int and double cannot be deduced to a single return type.

--------------------------------------------------

Advantages
----------

✔ Less boilerplate code
✔ Cleaner syntax
✔ Better readability
✔ Useful in template/generic code
✔ Eliminates the need for trailing return types in many cases

--------------------------------------------------

Most Asked Interview Questions
------------------------------

Q. Why wasn't this allowed in C++11?
A. C++11 couldn't deduce a function's return type from its body, so a trailing return type (`->`) was required.

Q. How does the compiler deduce the return type?
A. It examines all return statements and infers one common return type.

Q. Can different return statements have different types?
A. No. All return statements must deduce to the same type; otherwise compilation fails.

Q. Is return type deduction done at runtime?
A. No. It is performed at compile time.

